== SUBJECT LINE ==
Simple and clean. Under 10 words. Just the role and name, or one sharp descriptor.
Example: "Applied ML Engineer — Anshika Bajpai" / "ML Engineer, Indiana University May 2026 — Anshika Bajpai"

== OPENING LINE ==
One sentence. A universal truth or sharp insight about the problem space this role lives in.
Not about {{ company }}. Not about Anshika. A broader observation that makes the reader nod.
Fresh — written specifically for this role at {{ company }}.
Examples of the right KIND of opener (do not copy, write a new one):
- "Every AI project I've worked on eventually ran into the same bottleneck: inference."
- "The hardest part of building an AI product isn't the model — it's keeping it working at 3am."
- "Most ML systems work perfectly in notebooks. Making them work in production is a different problem entirely."

== PARAGRAPH 1 — Why {{ company }} (3–4 sentences) ==
Explain what {{ company }} is doing and why it is specifically interesting.
"Most companies do X. {{ company }} is doing Y — and Y is the harder, more important problem."
This should feel like an observation from someone who actually thought about the company, not a line from their About page.
Then: one sentence introducing Anshika — Master's in Data Science, Indiana University, May 2026, actual years of experience from her background.

== PARAGRAPH 2 — Real experience (4–5 sentences) ==
Lead with her most relevant work experience from her background. Use the exact company name and role title.
Explain what she was working on and WHY — what problem she was solving, not just what she did.
Include real metrics from her background. **Bold** the strongest one.
Add a second work experience or project briefly if relevant.
Connect to what {{ company }} is building.

== PARAGRAPH 3 — Personal project + genuine interest (3–4 sentences) ==
Pick the most relevant personal project from her background.
Describe what it does and what drives her to work on it.
End with a "what keeps me working on it" insight — something that reveals genuine intellectual interest, not just technical capability.
This paragraph should feel personal, not professional.

== PARAGRAPH 4 — Long-term vision (3–4 sentences) ==
Where does Anshika want to take her career long-term?
Why does {{ company }} specifically fit that direction?
What is the specific combination of work at {{ company }} that excites her — name actual things they do (inference, distributed systems, model serving, etc. — pulled from the JD or general knowledge).
This paragraph must not work for any other company. It should only make sense for {{ company }}.
Phrases like "I believe in end-to-end ownership", "I want to build things that last", "I care about impact, not demos" are good here.

== CLOSING LINE ==
One sentence. Specific to {{ company }} and what they're building.
Ties her vision to their mission. Can use "I'd love to" if it feels genuine.
NOT: "I look forward to hearing from you", "I am eager to", "Thank you for your consideration."
Examples:
- "If {{ company }} is trying to [specific thing], I'd love to help build that."
- "I'm ready to own [specific thing at {{ company }}] from day one."
- "When [specific challenge at {{ company }}] comes up, I want to be the one solving it."

